<!-- QUICK FIX GUIDE -->
<div class="section">
  <div class="section-label">Problem Solving</div>
  <h2>Photo Came Out Wrong? Fix It Fast.</h2>
  <div class="fix-grid">
    <div class="fix-card">
      <div class="fix-problem">🌑 Too Dark</div>
      <div class="fix-solution">
        Press <code>±</code> button → dial to <code>+1 EV</code><br>
        Or: raise ISO one stop<br>
        Or: open aperture wider (lower f/ number)<br>
        Or: slow shutter speed slightly
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="fix-card">
      <div class="fix-problem">☀️ Too Bright / Washed Out</div>
      <div class="fix-solution">
        Press <code>±</code> button → dial to <code>-1 EV</code><br>
        Or: raise shutter speed<br>
        Or: close aperture (higher f/ number)<br>
        Or: lower ISO
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="fix-card">
      <div class="fix-problem">🌀 Blurry / Motion Blur</div>
      <div class="fix-solution">
        Shutter too slow. Increase to <code>1/125</code> minimum for people.<br>
        For moving subjects: <code>1/500+</code><br>
        Compensate by raising ISO.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="fix-card">
      <div class="fix-problem">🟡 Weird Color / Yellow Cast</div>
      <div class="fix-solution">
        Change White Balance.<br>
        Indoors: try <code>Tungsten</code> or <code>Fluorescent</code><br>
        Outdoors: try <code>Daylight</code> or <code>Cloudy</code><br>
        Or use <code>Auto WB</code> — reliable on R10.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="fix-card">
      <div class="fix-problem">😶 Face Not in Focus</div>
      <div class="fix-solution">
        Check AF mode: set to <code>Face+Tracking</code><br>
        Half-press shutter to lock focus before shooting.<br>
        Reposition — R10 needs to "see" the face.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="fix-card">
      <div class="fix-problem">🌫 Background Too Sharp</div>
      <div class="fix-solution">
        Open aperture wider: <code>f/2.8</code> or lower.<br>
        Move subject farther from the background.<br>
        Move yourself closer to the subject.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- UNDER PRESSURE PROTOCOL -->
<div class="section">
  <div class="section-label">Under Pressure</div>
  <h2>The 10-Second Reset Protocol</h2>
  <p style="font-size:12px;color:var(--muted);margin-bottom:16px;">When you're in a new location and need great shots fast, run through this checklist before you start shooting.</p>

  <div class="protocol-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Read the light first</h4>
      <p>Look at where the light is coming from — window, sun, lamp. Is it bright or dark? This determines your starting ISO. Bright outdoors → <code>ISO 100</code>. Dark indoors → start at <code>ISO 1600</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="protocol-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Set your mode to Av</h4>
      <p>Turn the dial to <code>Av</code>. Set aperture to <code>f/2.8</code> as your starting point for most situations. This gives you control over blur and lets the camera handle shutter.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="protocol-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Take one test shot of your hand</h4>
      <p>Shoot your hand or a nearby surface. Check the result — is it bright enough? In focus? Adjust ISO up or down until you're happy. This is your calibration shot.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="protocol-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Use Exposure Compensation as your real-time dial</h4>
      <p>The <code>±</code> button on the back is your fastest correction tool. Subject looks dark? Go to <code>+1</code>. Washed out? Go to <code>-1</code>. This is faster than changing ISO mid-shoot.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="protocol-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Enable Face + Tracking before anything else</h4>
      <p>Go to AF Method → set to <code>Face+Tracking</code>. Leave it there for every portrait situation. The R10's AI will lock onto eyes and follow the subject. You focus on composing, not chasing focus.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- SKILL BUILDING EXERCISES -->
<div class="section">
  <div class="section-label">Skill Builder</div>
  <h2>5 Exercises That Build Real Camera Muscle</h2>

  <div class="exercise">
    <div class="exercise-header">
      <div class="exercise-num">01</div>
      <div>
        <h3>The Aperture Walk</h3>
        <div class="exercise-level level-beginner">● Beginner · Week 1</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="exercise-body">
      Find one subject — a flower, a candle, a friend's face. Shoot it 5 times without moving. Each shot, only change the aperture: f/2.8, f/4, f/5.6, f/8, f/11. Do not change anything else. Then review all 5 on your phone and observe what happens to the background blur and brightness as the number changes. This single exercise teaches you more than any YouTube video.
    </div>
    <div class="exercise-goal">🎯 Goal: Visually understand what each f-stop looks like so you can predict the result before you shoot.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="exercise">
    <div class="exercise-header">
      <div class="exercise-num">02</div>
      <div>
        <h3>The ISO Noise Test</h3>
        <div class="exercise-level level-beginner">● Beginner · Week 1</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="exercise-body">
      Set your camera to Manual mode. Keep aperture at f/2.8 and shutter at 1/100. Take one photo at each ISO: 100, 400, 800, 1600, 3200, 6400. Look at each photo at 100% zoom on your phone or computer. You'll see exactly where the R10 starts to show grain. Once you know this threshold, you'll always know how high you can push before quality suffers.
    </div>
    <div class="exercise-goal">🎯 Goal: Know your camera's ISO ceiling so you never under- or over-compensate in the dark.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="exercise">
    <div class="exercise-header">
      <div class="exercise-num">03</div>
      <div>
        <h3>The Light Relocation Drill</h3>
        <div class="exercise-level level-mid">◆ Intermediate · Week 2</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="exercise-body">
      Use one window in your home. Take a portrait of someone (or yourself with a timer) in 4 different positions relative to the window: facing it directly, 45° side-lit, 90° side-lit (dramatic), and back to the window. Same settings each time — just move the person. Review them side by side. This teaches you that light placement beats expensive gear every single time. The difference between these four shots is dramatic.
    </div>
    <div class="exercise-goal">🎯 Goal: Learn to "see" light direction and use it intentionally on any shoot.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="exercise">
    <div class="exercise-header">
      <div class="exercise-num">04</div>
      <div>
        <h3>The 60-Second Location Recalibration</h3>
        <div class="exercise-level level-pressure">▲ Pressure Training · Week 3</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="exercise-body">
      Go somewhere new — a restaurant, a park, a friend's living room. You have 60 seconds to get one great shot before your "subject" moves. Run the 10-Second Reset Protocol: read the light, set Av mode, set f/2.8, take a calibration test shot, adjust ISO and Exposure Compensation, then shoot for real. Repeat this drill weekly in different environments. This is exactly what it feels like to shoot content on location under time pressure — the same pressure you feel at events. Build the habit until it's instinct.
    </div>
    <div class="exercise-goal">🎯 Goal: Get comfortable making fast decisions in unfamiliar light so you stop relying on Auto.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="exercise">
    <div class="exercise-header">
      <div class="exercise-num">05</div>
      <div>
        <h3>The Re-Shoot</h3>
        <div class="exercise-level level-pressure">▲ Advanced · Ongoing</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="exercise-body">
      Go back through your G7X photos — find the ones that "could have been fire" but came out dark or washed out. Recreate those same shots with your R10 using what you now know. Shoot the same type of scene, same vibe, same framing. Compare old vs. new. This exercise is powerful because you already know exactly what you wanted — now you're learning to execute it technically. You'll feel the difference immediately and it'll lock in your muscle memory.
    </div>
    <div class="exercise-goal">🎯 Goal: Turn past frustrations into technical wins and build visual confidence in your own eye.</div>
  </div>
</div>

